<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much mulch do I need for a 100 square foot bed?", answer: "For a 100 square foot garden bed at the recommended 3 inch depth, you need 25 cubic feet of mulch, which is 0.93 cubic yards, or 13 bags of the standard 2 cubic foot bag. At 2 inches you need 16.7 cubic feet (0.62 cubic yards), and at 4 inches you need 33.3 cubic feet (1.23 cubic yards)." },
  { question: "How deep should mulch be?", answer: "A 2 to 3 inch layer is the sweet spot for most landscape beds. Less than 2 inches will break down too quickly and fail to suppress weeds, while more than 4 inches can suffocate plant roots, trap moisture against tree trunks, and cause disease. Refresh mulch once a year, adding just enough to top back up to 3 inches rather than piling new layers on top of old, compacted mulch." },
  { question: "How many cubic yards in a cubic foot?", answer: "One cubic yard equals 27 cubic feet, because a yard is 3 feet, and 3 × 3 × 3 = 27. Landscape suppliers sell mulch in bulk cubic yards at a significant discount compared to bags, typically at 30 to 50 percent less per cubic foot once you cross the threshold of about 2 or 3 yards, which is where delivery becomes cost-effective." },
  { question: "How many bags of mulch equal a yard?", answer: "At the most common bag size of 2 cubic feet, you need 13.5 bags to make a cubic yard. At 3 cubic feet per bag, it is 9 bags. Most big-box stores sell 2 cubic foot bags; some garden centers still carry the older 3 cubic foot bag, and some bulk mulch is sold in 1 cubic foot bags, which take 27 bags to make a yard." },
  { question: "Does mulch type affect how much I need?", answer: "No. Volume is volume regardless of material. Whether you are buying shredded hardwood, pine bark nuggets, cedar, cypress, rubber, or dyed wood, the cubic feet and cubic yards come out the same from the length × width × depth formula. The only thing that changes is the weight and the price per cubic foot. Rubber mulch is the heaviest, hardwood is medium, and pine bark is the lightest for a given volume." }
]) %>

